# Auth middleware chain

## Rule
Every authenticated route on an EFP backend plugs into the chain in order:

`Token → Tenant → User → Company → Role → EfpMiddleware`

Routes that legitimately skip Tenant (e.g., cross-tenant admin paths) must be explicit and reviewed.

## Why
The chain is the contract between Skipper, fy-iam-go, and the service. Each middleware assumes the previous one ran. Token (without Tenant) opens tenant-agnostic DB scans; Tenant (without User) hides per-user auditing.

## Constraints
- A new route registers middlewares in the defined order; none is silently dropped.
- API-key endpoints (`fbratesgoapikey`, `fbiqsapikey`, `BACKEND_SERVICE_API_KEY`, `RATE_AGENT_API_KEY`, `QA_AGENT_API_KEY`) are the only exception; those live in a separate route group and never mix JWT auth with key auth.
- `EfpMiddleware` (feature gating) runs last; tests must cover the case where the tenant lacks the required EFP feature.
- When adding a public (unauthenticated) route, document it in the repo's `service-communication.md` and get it added to Skipper routes explicitly.

## Examples

### Good (Go, Gin)
```go
efp := router.Group("/api/efp")
efp.Use(mw.Token(), mw.Tenant(), mw.User(), mw.Company(), mw.Role(), mw.Efp())
efp.GET("/tariff/:id", h.GetTariff)
```

### Bad
```go
// Tenant skipped - any tenant can read any tariff
efp := router.Group("/api/efp")
efp.Use(mw.Token(), mw.User())
efp.GET("/tariff/:id", h.GetTariff)
```

